snippet.textDisplay: I thought you were a food scientist? Adding salt does raise the boiling point of water ... but not enough to matter one single bit culinarily. It takes 58 grams of salt to raise the boiling point of 1 kilogram of water by a whopping .5 Celsius. For you Americans out there, if you add 1/4 cup of salt to 4 cups of water, you would raise the boiling point from 212 F to 212.9 F. That's a whole lot of salt for a change that isn't going to impact cooking times. A few teaspoons of soy sauce isn't going to change the boiling point one bit.
snippet.textOriginal: I thought you were a food scientist? Adding salt does raise the boiling point of water ... but not enough to matter one single bit culinarily. It takes 58 grams of salt to raise the boiling point of 1 kilogram of water by a whopping .5 Celsius. For you Americans out there, if you add 1/4 cup of salt to 4 cups of water, you would raise the boiling point from 212 F to 212.9 F.
